{ Rather than learn a bunch of moves that you aren't likely to face in your own games, the opening philosophy at the Dojo is: KEEP IT SIMPLE.

You should only memorize the basic moves of each key variation presented in this study. The core of your understanding of the positions should come from playing sparring matches against similarly rated players from the provided sparring positions. Analyze those games, discuss with your opponents, and you are sure to learn relevant middlegame strategy better than any long sequence of engine-generated moves could provide you. }
 *


[Event "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS: Introduction to the Caro-Kann"]
[Date "2023.12.06"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Introduction to the Caro-Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/gRKJ9I5D"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.12.06"]
[UTCTime "15:03:53"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Alright, enough talk! It's time to learn the Caro-Kann.

The fundamental idea of the Caro-Kann is to fight for the light squares in the center. Specifically, we want to challenge the e4 pawn with d5 without:
1. Closing the c8 bishop in as with the French defense.
2. Moving our queen out early with Qxd5 as in the Scandinavian defense.

In return, Black is down an extra tempo when the center closes compared to the French variations, and the b8 knight is (temporarily!?) blocked from its favorite square: c6. We'll see how this plays out in the relevant sections.

So let's learn the basics here like a BOSS. Then you can find a buddy, and start sparring! }
 *


[Event "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS: Section 1: Main line (3. Nc3 dxe4)"]
[Date "2023.06.07"]
[White "Caro"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Jesse"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Tartakower Variation"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Section 1: Main line (3. Nc3 dxe4)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/1KZ4hbum"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 (2. Nc3 { The Two Knights Caro. This variation is technically distinct from the main line, but our play is much the same as the main line. } 2... d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 { Nxf6 gives a similar position to the mainline and you can follow the middlegame plans suggested at the end of this section. } 5. Qe2!? (5. Nxf6+ exf6 $10 { With the Tartakower pawn structure. See Sparring position 1. }) 5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qa5! $10 { with the intention of Bf5 next move, developing our LSB outside the pawn chain with tempo. } { [%cal Gc8f5] }) 2... d5 { Black plays the main point behind the Caro-Kann by challenging the e4 pawn. } 3. Nc3 { This is usually considered the starting point of the (classical) main line. White develops a knight to defend the e4 pawn instead of releasing the tension. } (3. Nd2 { Another good move that directly transposes to the main line. } 3... dxe4! 4. Nxe4 { Transposing to the main line. }) 3... dxe4 { We take the chance to break White's center control since we have no other good developing move with our knights or bishops.
Nf6 would get popped with e5, gaining space. Nd7 doesn't adequately fight for the center and blocks in our LSB. e6 blocks in our LSB. } 4. Nxe4 { There are three acceptable moves from this position (Nf6, Bf5, Nd7) and you can choose another if you like, but the Dojo recommends Nf6.
The idea is to challenge the knight on e4, after which White can respond with Nxf6 (the focus of this chapter), Qd3 (suboptimal), or f3 (yuck). } 4... Nf6!? { The Tartakower variation } 5. Nxf6+ (5. Qd3 { Not a bad move, but it's not great to move the queen too often in the opening. } 5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Nd7 $10 { After Nf6 next, gaining a tempo on the queen, black can complete development. } { [%cal Gd7f6] }) (5. f3?! { Blocks in the g1 knight forever. As long as we do not capture on e4, this move only weakens white's kingside for no benefit. } 5... Nbd7 $15) 5... exf6 { Sparring Pos 1. Allowing easy development for our pieces and the f6 pawn will be useful in defending our kingside. } 6. c3!? (6. Bc4!? Bd6 { White can play Ne2, planning to castle, or Qe2, forcing a Queen trade.
Ne2 leads to a relatively passive position and your plans are similar to the mainline. } 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7! { This is a key move! The queens have been traded and there's no immediate danger, so we can keep our king in the center for the endgame. } 9. Ne2 Re8 $10) 6... Bd6 { Beyond this point, we should NOT focus on memorizing specific moves. The key ideas are to finish development and utilize our kingside pawn majority.
This is the most active square available for our bishop. } 7. Bd3 { Other squares are acceptable for our opponent's bishop, but this active square prevents us from playing Bf5 ourselves. } 7... O-O { Our opponent can play Qc2 or Ne2 first. Our response will be the same: Re8, taking control of the file before White can stop us. } 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5! { A key idea in this system! We claim that the kingside is our side of the board and make white fret over h4-h3. } 10. O-O!? { Placing the king on the kingside is a tame way for white to play. However, now we see another idea behind our earlier h5. } (10. Be3!? { White signals they are castling queenside. Therefore, pushing the h pawn further too soon would only help white open up our king. } 10... Nd7 { Note that the fundamental problem of the French is the bad LSB and for the Caro, the key challenge is finding employment for this knight. } 11. O-O-O { Our kingside pawn majority makes it harder for white to break through on the kingside. h5 effectively stops lines from opening up against our king. } 11... Nf8 { This knight move is key in this system and you'll do well to remember it. Depending on how White plays, both Ng6 and Ne6 could be good moves. } 12. Kb1 Be6 $132 { Even though our play so far has focused on developing quickly, we next will quickly mobilize our forces toward the queenside to launch an attack against White. The name of the game is opposite sides castling, so the race to see who will open up the other's king first begins. }) 10... h4! { Cramping white's e2 knight further, and threatening to offload the h pawn with h3, creating light squared weaknesses now that white has committed the king to the kingside. } 11. h3 Nd7 $132 { Black will have all the fun on the kingside while white must dream of creating something with their majority on the queenside. } *


