[UTCTime "15:03:53"]

{ Remember that in this position, we were capturing on e4, and then developing our pieces further, with an eventual attack on the centralized e4 queen. }
1... Nbd7?? { This "obvious" developing move is a terrible blunder, since it walks directly into the trap that white players are hoping for: } (1... Nxe4! 2. Qxe4 Qa5 $10 { with the intention of Bf5 next move, developing our LSB outside the pawn chain with tempo. Play continues. } { [%cal Gc8f5] }) 2. Nd6#! { Don't let this happen to you!
Before playing Nbd7, we need to see that the queen on e2 was both supporting the e4 knight and creating a pin on the e7 pawn. } *


[Event "Import"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/qhYbakma"]
[Date "2022.10.28"]
[White "Md., Shar"]
[Black "Gukesh, D."]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2205"]
[BlackElo "2614"]
[TimeControl "-"]
[Termination "Unknown"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Tartakower Variation"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Black's queenside attack breaks through first"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/gwNnEAfY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

1. e4 { Gukesh on the black side here launches a fearsome queenside attack in this opposite-sides castling game to break through to white's king first. } 1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5! 10. Be3 Nd7 11. O-O-O Nf8 12. Kb1 Be6 13. Nf4?! { As it turns out, our attack is mostly on the light squares. So while the next move might at first surprise you, it keeps our most important attacker alive, and doesn't lose tempo. } 13... Bxf4! 14. Bxf4 b5 { Black now launches the thematic queenside attack. } 15. b3 a5 16. Bc1 a4 17. b4 { Trying to keep the queenside closed just gives up the c4 square forever. Gukesh next seeks to occupy it. } 17... Nd7 18. Rde1 Nb6 19. Re2 Ra7 (19... Bc4!? { Also a good move, but there's no need to rush things. }) 20. Rhe1 Rae7 21. Ka1 Bc4! { Winning c4 for the knight. } 22. Bxc4 Nxc4 { Now we're in a good knight vs bad bishop position. Gukesh wins with style. } 23. Qd3 Qd6 24. h3 h4 25. Qf3 g6 26. Kb1 Kg7 27. Kc2 Re6 28. Rxe6 Rxe6 29. Rxe6 Qxe6 30. Kd1 a3 31. Qe2 Nb2+ 32. Kd2 (32. Bxb2?! Qxe2+ 33. Kxe2 axb2 $19) 32... Qxa2 33. Qe4 Nd3+ $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


[Event "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS: Section 2: Advance (3. e5)"]
[Date "2023.06.07"]
[White "Caro"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Jesse"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B12"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Advance Variation, Short Variation"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Section 2: Advance (3. e5)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/1evJWF1f"]

1. e4 c6 (1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { Compare and contrast the actual advanced French with the main line given in this chapter. }) 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { The Advanced variation of the Caro-Kann.
We have a French structure, where our bad bishop can get outside the pawn chain, but where we owe white a tempo (compared to the French defense) to play the all-important c5 pawn break and strike at their imposing center. } 3... Bf5 { Getting the bishop outside the pawn chain right away is a thematic idea in the Caro. } 4. Nf3!? { Sparring Pos 2. White can play a variety of developing moves, but the dynamic will be the same: we need to be careful about when we open the position with c5. } (4. h4!? { The beginning of the Tal variation is Sparring Pos 3. } 4... h5 { A necessary evil. We don't want to weaken our kingside further, but we need to stop white from expanding on the kingside before finishing development. } 5. Bg5!? (5. Bd3!? { It may seem weird for white to trade LSBs given the fixed pawns in the center. But the main point behind this move is to quickly develop and destroy us before we can untangle. } 5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 (7. Nd2 Qa6) 7... Qa6! $10 { With the same idea as against 5.Bg5. }) 5... Qb6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Qa6! $10 { Don't even be tempted to take on b2! White will move their Queen somewhere, and we will achieve stability with e6. }) (4. Bd3?! { A common move at the lower levels, but poor. This simply trades our bad bishop for white's most important attacker. } 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 $10 { See Nimzowitsch - Capablanca for a model game from this position. }) 4... e6 5. Be2 { This is a sample variation: the Short variation of the Advanced Caro-Kann.
It must be stressed: white can play any number of developing moves here. We need to know that c5 will always cost us a tempo AND will increase the value of time because we are opening the position. } 5... Nd7 6. O-O Ne7 { White can play many moves here. It's best to calmly build our position. } 7. Nbd2 h6 8. c3 Bh7 9. Nb3 Nf5 $10 { With a solid position. The dream is to achieve a good French with c5 when we are ready. } *


